description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/meshcore/adapter.c
Lines: 314-337

The function calculates output length and writes payload:
```c
static int encode_pending_text(const struct lichen_meshcore_pending_event *event,
                   uint8_t *out, size_t out_len)
{
    size_t len = LICHEN_MESHCORE_CHANNEL_MSG_V3_HEADER_LEN +
             event->payload_len;

    if (out == NULL || out_len < len) {
        return -ENOMEM;
    }
    // ... writes header ...
    if (event->payload_len > 0U) {
        memcpy(&out[LICHEN_MESHCORE_CHANNEL_MSG_V3_HEADER_LEN],
               event->payload, event->payload_len);
    }
    return (int)len;
}
```

The issue: event->payload_len is uint16_t. The addition at line 317-318 could theoretically exceed size_t on 16-bit platforms where size_t is 16 bits. However, on any reasonable platform (32-bit size_t), 11 + 65535 = 65546 fits.

More importantly, there's no check that event->payload_len <= sizeof(event->payload). If payload_len is corrupted or set incorrectly, the memcpy could read beyond the payload buffer.

At the emit_text entry point (line 1176-1179), there is a check:
```c
if (event->payload_len >
    LICHEN_MESHCORE_FRAME_MAX - LICHEN_MESHCORE_CHANNEL_MSG_V3_HEADER_LEN) {
    return -EMSGSIZE;
}
```

But this uses incoming event's payload_len, not the stored one. If pending->payload_len is corrupted after storage, no check catches it here.

Consider adding: assert(event->payload_len <= sizeof(event->payload));
